For the programming structure within [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) that utilizes [Lua](/Lua) code, you'll want to consult [Wikipedia:Module](/Wikipedia:Module). If your quest for definition is a more fundamental one, you might consider looking up "module" or "modular" in [Wiktionary](/Wiktionary), the free dictionary—though I suspect you're looking for something a bit more substantial than a mere lexical entry.

The terms **Module**, **modular**, and **modularity** are, as you might have surmised from the sheer volume of this list, incredibly versatile. They generally orbit around the core concept of [modularity](/Modularity) itself: the degree to which a system's components can be separated and recombined. A rather elegant idea, really, implying a certain order in a chaotic universe, or at least in human-made systems. But, as with all good ideas, humans have managed to apply it to an astonishing array of contexts, often with varying degrees of success or clarity. They may also refer to:

### Computer science and engineering

In the realm where logic and silicon meet, "module" is a foundational principle, though it manifests in diverse forms, each serving to manage the inherent complexity of building and understanding systems.

*   **[Modular design](/Modular_design)**: This is the engineering discipline that dictates the creation of complex devices through the assembly of separately designed, independent sub-components. Think of it as adult [Lego](/Lego), but with far higher stakes and considerably less colorful bricks. The benefit, ostensibly, is easier assembly, simplified maintenance, and the ability to upgrade specific parts without dismantling the entire edifice. It's a testament to the human desire to break down overwhelming problems into manageable, bite-sized pieces—a survival mechanism, really.
*   **[Modular function deployment](/Modular_function_deployment)**: A systematic methodology employed within [systems engineering](/Systems_engineering) and [product development](/Product_development). This approach focuses on translating customer requirements into design characteristics, and then further breaking these down into modular functions. It's a way to ensure that every component, every "module," directly contributes to the desired outcome, minimizing unnecessary complexity and maximizing efficiency, or so the theory goes.
*   **[Module (Gear)](/Gear)**: In mechanical engineering, specifically concerning [gears](/Gear), "module" is a precise measure of a gear's pitch. It defines the size of the teeth relative to the gear's diameter. It's a metric, expressed in millimeters, that ensures interoperability between gears; a critical detail, as incorrectly meshing gears tend to produce rather catastrophic results, or at least a lot of unpleasant noise. A surprisingly specific application for such a general term, wouldn't you agree?
*   **[Ontology modularization](/Ontology_modularization)**: A methodological principle essential in [ontology engineering](/Ontology_engineering). This involves breaking down large, complex [ontologies](/Ontology_(information_science))—which are essentially formal representations of knowledge—into smaller, more manageable modules. This enhances reusability, maintainability, and facilitates collaborative development, allowing multiple experts to work on different parts of a vast knowledge domain without stepping on each other's digital toes.

### Computer software

Software, by its very nature, thrives on modularity. Without it, you'd be looking at monolithic blocks of code that even their creators couldn't untangle.

*   **[Modular programming](/Modular_programming)**: A fundamental software design technique where a program is decomposed into smaller, independent, interchangeable components known as modules. Each module is designed to perform a distinct function, encapsulating its own data and logic. This approach dramatically improves code readability, maintainability, reusability, and makes debugging slightly less of a descent into madness. It’s a concept so obvious, one wonders why anyone ever wrote software any other way.
*   **[Java Platform Module System](/Java_Platform_Module_System)**: Introduced in [Java 9](/Java_version_history#Java_9), this system (often referred to as [Project Jigsaw](/Project_Jigsaw)) formalizes the concept of modules within the Java ecosystem. It aims to improve the security, maintainability, and performance of large Java applications by allowing developers to define explicit dependencies between modules and encapsulate internal implementation details. A necessary evolution, one might say, for a language that has grown to such a colossal scale.
*   **[Modules (C++)](/Modules_(C%2B%2B))**: A feature introduced in [C++20](/C++20) to address long-standing issues with the language's traditional header files, such as slow compilation times and macro-related problems. C++ modules offer a more robust and efficient way to organize and reuse code, providing stronger encapsulation and faster build processes. It's C++ finally catching up, in some respects, to concepts that have been around for decades.
*   **[Module SQL](/Module_SQL)**: Within the [SQL](/SQL) standard, "module" refers to a collection of related [SQL](/SQL) routines (like procedures and functions) that can be compiled and stored together. It provides a way to logically group database operations and enhance reusability and organization of code within a database system.
*   **[Loadable kernel module](/Loadable_kernel_module)**: In operating systems like [Linux](/Linux), these are object files containing code that can extend the running kernel of the operating system. They allow system functionality to be added or removed while the system is running, without needing to reboot the entire kernel. This is incredibly useful for device drivers or new file systems, enabling dynamic configuration without the inconvenience of constant system restarts.
*   **[Environment Modules](/Modules_Environment)**: A software tool designed to simplify the management of a user's [Unix](/Unix) or [Linux shell environment](/Shell_(computing)). It allows users to dynamically load and unload different versions of software packages, compilers, and libraries without conflicts, which is particularly invaluable in shared computing environments or for developers needing to switch between various project configurations.
*   **[Modula-2](/Modula-2) or [Modula-3](/Modula-3)**: These are programming languages, descendants of [Pascal](/Pascal_(programming_language)), that explicitly stress and enforce the use of modules as a primary structuring mechanism. Developed by [Niklaus Wirth](/Niklaus_Wirth) (the creator of Pascal), Modula-2 was designed to be a systems programming language, while Modula-3 was an evolution focused on safety and robustness. They championed the idea of separate compilation and clear interfaces long before many other languages fully embraced these principles.

### Computer hardware

Even the tangible world of electronics benefits from the modular approach, allowing for greater flexibility and repairability, assuming you have the right tools and a modicum of patience.

*   **[Computer module](/Computer_module)**: An early packaging technique in electronics that combined several discrete electronic components—such as resistors, capacitors, and transistors—into a single, encapsulated unit. These modules were designed to produce a single logic element or function, simplifying assembly and improving reliability in the nascent days of computing.
*   **[Memory module](/Memory_module)**: This refers to the physical "stick" of [RAM](/Random-access_memory) (Random-Access Memory) that you slot into a computer's [motherboard](/Motherboard). It's an absolutely essential piece of computer hardware, providing the volatile working memory for the [CPU](/Central_processing_unit). Without it, your computer is little more than an expensive paperweight. These modules come in various forms, such as [DIMMs](/DIMM) or [SODIMMs](/SO-DIMM), each designed for specific system architectures.
*   **[Multi-chip module](/Multi-chip_module)**: A modern packaging technique that integrates multiple complex computer chips (e.g., a [CPU](/Central_processing_unit), [GPU](/Graphics_processing_unit), and [memory](/Memory_(computing))) onto a single substrate. This creates a more compact, higher-performing, and often more power-efficient unit than if the chips were packaged individually. It's about getting more processing power into a smaller footprint, which is, of course, the eternal goal.

### Science and mathematics

In the abstract realms, "module" frequently denotes a structured collection or a specific mathematical object that exhibits certain properties. It's where the term truly gets to flex its intellectual muscles.

*   **[Module (mathematics)](/Module_(mathematics))**: This is a fundamental concept in [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra). A module over a [ring](/Ring_(mathematics)) is a generalization of the notion of a [vector space](/Vector_space), where the scalars are elements of an arbitrary ring instead of a [field](/Field_(mathematics)). Modules are central to many areas of mathematics, providing a rich framework for studying algebraic structures and their properties. Definitely not for the mathematically faint of heart.
*   **G -module over a group G**: Within the intricate tapestry of abstract algebra, particularly in the realm of [group theory](/Group_theory), one encounters the concept of a G -module over a group G. This is essentially an [abelian group](/Abelian_group) upon which the group G acts in a compatible way, extending the ideas of modules over rings to a different algebraic structure. It's a specific kind of structure that mathematicians, in their infinite pursuit of generalization, found both necessary and elegant.
*   **[Modular lattice](/Modular_lattice)**: In [order theory](/Order_theory), a modular lattice is a specific kind of [partially ordered set](/Partially_ordered_set) that satisfies a particular condition known as the modular law. This property makes them amenable to certain algebraic manipulations and allows for a richer theory compared to general lattices.
*   **[Modularity theorem](/Modularity_theorem)** (formerly known as the [Taniyama–Shimura conjecture](/Taniyama–Shimura_conjecture)): This is a profound result in [number theory](/Number_theory) that establishes a deep connection between two seemingly disparate mathematical objects: [elliptic curves](/Elliptic_curve) and [modular forms](/Modular_form). Its proof, completed in 2001, was a monumental achievement, famously providing the key to [Andrew Wiles's](/Andrew_Wiles) proof of [Fermat's Last Theorem](/Fermat's_Last_Theorem). A truly elegant demonstration of how different mathematical "modules" can be connected.
*   Module, in connection with [modular decomposition](/Modular_decomposition): In [graph theory](/Graph_theory), modular decomposition is a technique for analyzing the structure of a graph by breaking it down into smaller, simpler subgraphs called modules. These modules are a kind of generalization of [graph components](/Connected_component_(graph_theory)), representing sets of vertices that behave identically with respect to the rest of the graph.
*   **[Modularity (networks)](/Modularity_(networks))**: This is a benefit function used in the analysis of [complex networks](/Complex_network), such as social networks or biological networks. It measures the quality of a division of a network into "communities" or clusters. A high modularity value indicates that nodes within the same community are densely connected to each other, but sparsely connected to nodes in other communities. It's a quantitative way to assess how well a network can be broken down into semi-independent functional units.
*   **Protein module or [protein domain](/Protein_domain)**: In [molecular biology](/Molecular_biology), this refers to a distinct section of a [protein](/Protein) that has its own unique, stable [conformation](/Protein_folding) and often a specific biological function. These domains are frequently conserved across different proteins and species throughout [evolution](/Evolution), acting like reusable building blocks that nature employs to construct diverse proteins with varied functions.
*   A **cis -regulatory module**: In [genetics](/Genetics), this is a stretch of [DNA](/DNA) that contains a number of [gene](/Gene)s that share joint regulation by the same [transcription factors](/Transcription_factor). These modules act as switches, controlling when and where genes are expressed, demonstrating a highly modular and coordinated system for gene regulation.

### Music

Even the ephemeral world of sound and rhythm finds structure in modules, allowing for new forms of creation and expression.

*   **[Module (musician)](/Module_(musician))**: This is the solo project undertaken by the New Zealand-based musician and producer, [Jeramiah Ross](/Jeramiah_Ross). An artist choosing a name that embodies self-contained creation, perhaps.
*   **[Module file](/Module_file)**: This refers to a family of music file formats, such as [MOD](/MOD_(file_format)), [S3M](/S3M), [XM](/XM_(file_format)), and [IT](/Impulse_Tracker), that combine instrument samples and pattern data into a single file. These files were popular in the [demoscene](/Demoscene) and early [video game music](/Video_game_music) for their compact size and ability to produce complex musical arrangements with limited resources.
*   **[Modular Recordings](/Modular_Recordings)**: An independent record label, founded in [Sydney, Australia](/Sydney), known for signing and developing artists primarily in the [indie rock](/Indie_rock) and [electronic music](/Electronic_music) genres.
*   **[Modular synthesizer](/Modular_synthesizer)**: A type of electronic musical instrument composed of independent, interchangeable modules (e.g., [oscillators](/Electronic_oscillator), [filters](/Filter_(signal_processing)), [amplifiers](/Electronic_amplifier), [envelope generators](/Envelope_(music))). Users connect these modules with patch cables to create custom signal paths and generate a vast array of unique sounds. It's a highly flexible and experimental approach to sound design, appealing to those who enjoy building their instruments as much as playing them.
*   **[Sound module](/Sound_module)**: An electronic musical instrument that generates sounds but lacks a human-playable interface, such as a keyboard. Instead, it's controlled by an external device, typically a [MIDI controller](/MIDI_controller) or a [computer sequencer](/Sequencer). These modules are essentially the "brains" of a synthesizer without the physical interface, allowing musicians to expand their sonic palette without acquiring more full-sized instruments.

### Other uses

Beyond the confines of technology, science, and art, the concept of "module" permeates various aspects of human endeavor, often reflecting a desire for standardization and efficiency.

*   **[Modular building](/Modular_building)**: A construction method where prefabricated building sections, or "modules," are manufactured off-site in a factory setting and then transported to the construction site for assembly. These can be used for houses, offices, or other structures, offering advantages in terms of speed of construction, cost efficiency, and quality control. Some even embrace the spirit of [open source hardware](/Open_source_hardware), making designs freely available for others to adapt and build upon.
*   **[NTC Module](/NTC_Module)**: This refers to a Russian research and development center. Specific, yet still within the modular theme of a focused unit.
*   **[ModulArt](/ModulArt)**: An artistic technique employed in contemporary art where a large-scale painting or sculpture is composed of multiple smaller, individual modules. These modules can often be rearranged, allowing for dynamic compositions and interaction with the viewer, challenging traditional notions of a fixed artwork.
*   **[Ford Modular engine](/Ford_Modular_engine)**: This is Ford's specific line of overhead camshaft ([OHC](/Overhead_camshaft)) [V8](/V8_engine) and [V10](/V10_engine) motors, produced from 1990 to 2014. The "Modular" designation refers to the design philosophy that allowed for common cylinder bore spacing and other shared components across various displacements, facilitating efficient manufacturing and design.
*   **[Volvo Modular engine](/Volvo_Modular_engine)**: A series of straight-four, straight-five, and straight-six [internal combustion engines](/Internal_combustion_engine) produced by [Volvo Cars](/Volvo_Cars) from 1990 to 2016. Similar to Ford's approach, these engines shared a common architecture, allowing for modularity in production and design across different cylinder configurations.
*   **[Game module](/Game_module)** or expansion: In the context of [tabletop](/Tabletop_game) or [video games](/Video_game), this refers to an add-on publication or digital content that extends the base game. It might introduce new scenarios, characters, rules, or environments, effectively bolting new "modules" onto the core experience.
*   **[Adventure (Dungeons & Dragons)](/Adventure_(Dungeons_%26_Dragons))**: In the early days of the iconic [role-playing game](/Role-playing_game), [Dungeons & Dragons](/Dungeons_%26_Dragons), these pre-written scenarios or campaigns were often colloquially referred to as "modules." They provided a self-contained narrative and set of challenges for players to explore.
*   **[Vitruvian module](/Vitruvian_module)**: An architectural measure derived from the principles laid out by the ancient Roman architect [Vitruvius](/Vitruvius). It represents a fixed unit of proportion used to establish the dimensions of various elements within a classical building, ensuring harmony and balance throughout the structure.
*   A class, [course](/Course_(education)), or unit of education covering a single topic: In academic or professional training contexts, a "module" often denotes a self-contained unit of study, typically focused on a specific subject area or skill. It's a way of packaging knowledge into digestible, sequential blocks.
*   **[Modular AI](/Modular_AI)**: This refers to an American company operating in the field of [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence).

